# Copy to .env.local for local-only secrets (never commit .env.local).
# Example:
# REACT_APP_EMAILJS_SERVICE_ID=
# REACT_APP_EMAILJS_TEMPLATE_ID=
# REACT_APP_EMAILJS_PUBLIC_KEY=

# =============================================================================
# Spotify — server-side only (your account, no visitor OAuth)
# =============================================================================
# Set these in Vercel → Project → Settings → Environment Variables (Production).
# Never prefix server secrets with REACT_ — they must not ship in the client bundle.
#
# SPOTIFY_CLIENT_ID=
# SPOTIFY_CLIENT_SECRET=
# SPOTIFY_REFRESH_TOKEN=
#
# Optional:
# SPOTIFY_CORS_ORIGINS=http://127.0.0.1:3000,http://localhost:3000
#
# Scopes when issuing the refresh token:
# user-read-currently-playing, user-read-recently-played, user-top-read
#
# One-time refresh token (run once on your machine):
# 1. Fill SPOTIFY_CLIENT_ID + SPOTIFY_CLIENT_SECRET in .env.local
# 2. Spotify Dashboard → Redirect URIs → add exactly: http://127.0.0.1:4399/callback
# 3. Development mode? Dashboard → Users and Access → add your Spotify account email
# 4. npm run spotify:token → approve in browser → copy printed SPOTIFY_REFRESH_TOKEN into .env.local + Vercel
#
# --- Local dev (pick one) ---
#
# A) npm start — frontend only; Spotify needs the deployed API (or use B).
#
# B) npm run dev (easiest — local API + React, no Vercel CLI)
#    SPOTIFY_* in .env.local, then: npm install && npm run dev
#    Open http://localhost:3000 — test http://localhost:3000/api/spotify/feed
#
# C) npm run dev:api — Vercel CLI (vercel login + vercel link first)
#
# --- Deploy (fixes npm start + production site) ---
# 1. Push this repo and deploy on Vercel.
# 2. Add SPOTIFY_CLIENT_ID, SPOTIFY_CLIENT_SECRET, SPOTIFY_REFRESH_TOKEN in Vercel env.
# 3. Redeploy. Test: https://www.aurickanwar.com/api/spotify/current-playing → JSON, not HTML.
#
# Optional override (only if API is on another host):
# REACT_APP_SPOTIFY_API_BASE=https://www.aurickanwar.com
